<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Twilight Pool and your Shadow deck<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.82)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8814'>Michael "mearleycf" Earley</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8814&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 11, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> OK, I slowly came to the realization last night, after playing the game for about a month now, that I&#39;ve been completely ignoring a major facet of deck building--twilight costs. <br>
<br>
Specifically, we, as builders of shadow decks, have the distinct advantage of knowing, approximately, how much twilight pool we will have to work with in two situations: 1) the whole game, and 2) at each site. However, up until this point I&#39;ve not considered the ramifications of that advantage! <br>
<br>
Let me break it down: <br>
<br>
The fellowship player will only put a certain number of twilight tokens into the twilight pool during a given game or given turn. This number is a rough calculation of the following : 1) site cost, 2) movement cost, 3) fellowship card being played, 4) fellowship action being performed from card already in play. <br>
<br>
I won&#39;t focus on 4, as it&#39;s impact to the shadow pool, relatively speaking, is negligible (sp?). <br>
<br>
SITES <br>
<br>
Your opponent, in a complete &quot;move to site 9&quot; game, will move 8 times. In those 8 moves, your opponent will put the following into the shadow pool: <br>
1 to 2: 1 to 3 tokens (avg 1.6) <br>
2 to 3: 0 tokens <br>
3 to 4: 2 to 3 tokens (avg 2.6) <br>
4 to 5: 6 tokens <br>
5 to 6: 3 tokens <br>
6 to 7: 6 tokens <br>
7 to 8: 6 to 9 tokens (avg 6.8) <br>
8 to 9: 8 to 9 tokens (avg 8.8) <br>
<br>
Averaging out, that&#39;s 35.8 tokens, or 36 tokens, from movement alone. <br>
<br>
COMPANIONS <br>
<br>
You have to have 1 companion to win the game, so we know there will be at least 8 more added to the pool for that one companion (frodo or sam). <br>
<br>
From there, here are my ROUGH estimates on companions: <br>
<br>
100% chance of one companion = 8 tokens <br>
98% chance of two companions = 8 tokens <br>
87.5% chance of 3 companions = 7 tokens <br>
75% chance of 4 companions = 6 tokens <br>
50% chance of 5 companions = 4 tokens <br>
12.5% chance of 6 companions = 1 token <br>
<br>
More than 7 companions is statistically unlikely, and will not be figured here. <br>
<br>
What I&#39;ve done here is not an exact science (I&#39;m not a statistician), but it&#39;s close enough for horseshoes and LoTR. <br>
<br>
Therefore, the companions will add appx 34 more tokens from movement. <br>
<br>
FELLOWSHIP CARDS PLAYED <br>
<br>
The average cost of the companions is 1.92, so we&#39;ll round up to 2. You&#39;ll start with 4 points of companions, and are likely to add at least 1 more companion (2 points), probably 2 (2 more points). Since often that companion is going to be Aragorn or Gandalf, I&#39;m going to add 2 for my own sanity. That&#39;s 6 points you&#39;ll add for companions, on average. <br>
<br>
Again guessing, that leaves appx 24-30 cards in the fellowship deck. The average deck appears to be about 70 (35 per side), and the average cost of fellowship non-companion cards is appx 1 token per (i.e. some will cost 4, some will cost 0). So--take out appx 5 for companions, that leaves 30 cards, each at 1 token. <br>
<br>
So: <br>
<br>
On average, you can expect the following for a fellowship token pool: 36 for sites, 34 for movement, 6 for companions, 30 for other fellowship plays. <br>
<br>
That brings our total to 34+36+30+6=106 points of twilight pool played into the pool through the whole game (not including no stranger to shadows, which can remove as many as 20 twilight tokens, and Talent for Not Being Seen, which could remove as many as 14, and Glamdring, Sting, The Gaffer&#39;s Pipe. <br>
<br>
let&#39;s round down to 95, considering your opponent will probably have ONE of these cards in their deck. <br>
<br>
What does this all mean? Well, it&#39;s important the your deck fits this balance. Too few shadow cards means you aren&#39;t taking advantage of the pool appropriately, and too many high-cost cards means you won&#39;t use it effectively either. <br>
<br>
My theory/strategy is this: when building your shadow deck, don&#39;t put more than appx 110 or so twilight points into that deck. Build your deck so that you are maximizing the twilight pool that your opponent will create (i.e. don&#39;t take 4 &quot;Beauty is Fading&quot;, 4 &quot;Witch King&quot;, etc., where your deck isn&#39;t playable b/c of cost!). <br>
<br>
You&#39;d be surprised at how quickly those shadow cards add up. Do you feel like your deck is going to slow? You may have too much shadow. Too fast, not enough at site 9? Not enough utilization of twilight. <br>
<br>
SITE TO SITE--TURN AVAILABILITY <br>
<br>
Now that you&#39;ve built your deck, most of you are going to play it (I&#39;m POSITIVE that there are folks out there who just build decks and never play them). How do you play this masterful shadow deck you&#39;ve just built? <br>
<br>
Get out the calculator again... <br>
<br>
First...I&#39;m going to loosely illustrate what I believe the purchase of possessions and companions, across the 9 fellowship turns, is going to be. We&#39;ve stated earlier that your opponent will have 36 Twilight points of fellowship to play (30 cards at 1 per, and 6 points of companions). 9 fellowship phases means that&#39;s 4 per turn. However, I don&#39;t believe the distribution is that clean. Specifically, here is my LOOSE (totally opinion-based) curve of point distribution during fellowship phases: <br>
<br>
- assume 8 of the 36 points will be spent outside fellowship phase <br>
- assume your opponent will NOT buy anything at the site 4 fellowship phase, moving to site 5 <br>
- assume your opponent will move 2 sites at least one time <br>
<br>
That leaves 28 points to distribute over 7 fellowship phases (clean math:)), so still 4 points per phase. Let&#39;s do the distribution like this: <br>
<br>
Site 1: 6 points <br>
Site 2: 5 points <br>
Site 3: 4 points <br>
Site 4: 0 points <br>
Site 5: 5 points <br>
Site 6: 4 points <br>
Site 7: 4 points <br>
Site 8: 0 points (assume they pushed here) <br>
<br>
Site 1 to 2: average twilight is 1.6. Your opponent WILL have at least 2 companions (except in a Frodo Alone deck). Therefor your opponent will play approximately 9.6 points into twilight during this turn. <br>
<br>
Site 2 to 3: move twilight is 0, plus at least 2 companions, probably 3 or 4. Let&#39;s say 3.5. Add 5 for cards played, that&#39;s 8.5 points into twilight this turn. <br>
<br>
Site 3 to 4: move twilight averages 2.6, plus 4 companions, plus 4 points--10.6 into twilight. <br>
<br>
Site 4 to 5: twilight = 6, plus 4 companions, plus 0 points - 10 points into twilight. <br>
<br>
Site 5 to 6: twilight = 3, plus 3.5 companions (50/50 chance one has died by now...:)), plus 5 points spent = 11.5 points. <br>
<br>
Site 6 to 7 = 6 tokens, plus 4 for companions (they got another out late), plus 6 for purchases, wow--16 tokens! Sounds high...but we&#39;ll trust our figures for now. <br>
<br>
Site 7 to 8: twilight = 6.8, 4 companions, 4 points bought. 16.8 available. <br>
<br>
Site 8 to 9: twilight = 8.8, 3 companions, 0 points bought = 11.8. <br>
<br>
What does all of this mean? Obiously games will almost never play perfectly, in terms of statistics. However--what this means is that you need to look at your card choices VERY closely when choosing a deck. Have a sweet combination of exhausting companions then killing them with archery? How much did it cost--15 points worth of twilight? You probably won&#39;t get it off. Plan on using &quot;Beauty is Fading&quot; in combination with Lemanya and Sword of Minas Morgul, to rip Aragorn&#39;s equipment to shreds? You&#39;d better have 13 points at site 2, or 11 after that. Specifically, make sure your combos don&#39;t cost more than 10 twilight points to play, or if it&#39;s a late game combo, maybe 11 or 12 points. <br>
<br>
Furthermore, focus on killing companions. If all you do is wound your opponent, and he heals at sites 3 and 6, and you never kill the companions, you&#39;ve lost. Put in 10 point combinations that will KILL a companion, or significantly wound them. <br>
<br>
Finally, don&#39;t plan on utilizing the same card too many ways. Look at your deck, plan it out, turn by turn. I&#39;ve already said you&#39;ll only play about 90 points of twilight, and this is born out by my site analysis. Try laying a &quot;sample&quot; play of your shadow deck out, based off your sites, then again without using your sites (and their minion-cost-lowering abilities). What would you play in turn 1? turn 3? turn 7? turn 9? Do your plays come in for an acceptable cost? Can you mitigate some of that cost to get a better combination? If you lay your deck out and you can&#39;t figure out how you&#39;ll do anything with it on a site-by-site basis, you may need to rebuild it. <br>
<br>
ROAMING COSTS AND THEIR IMPACT <br>
<br>
One last thought--don&#39;t forget about the roaming costs. Yes, Nazgul are expensive. Yes, they lose roaming cost early and morgul gates mitigates their cost to a degree. However--I guarantee if you include all witch kings, toldeas, and other 6-cost nazgul only in your deck, you won&#39;t ever win a game, no matter how many Bree Streets, Fords of Bruinen, Morgul Gates, and Morgul Stalkers you use in your deck, b/c you&#39;ll never get the right playability out of that deck! It&#39;s too expensive. <br>
<br>
Roaming costs hurt Uruk-Hai and Sauron more than any culture, as the Moria quit roaming early and are usually cheaper anyway. However, this means, to me, that the condition/cheap minion combos are more important early on in Uruk-Hai and Sauron decks, that may not be able to get those expensive minions out till site 5 or 6. <br>
<br>
I&#39;m a strong proponent of including cards in the shadow deck (not a bunch, but a few), that may be expensive to bring out (beauty is fading, alive and unspoiled), but are less expensive at early sites than their minion counterparts. In other words, playing an uruk-hai deck, I may want to try and save some of my more powerful uruk hai for later rounds (sites 4 and above maybe), while utilizing some conditions and events and cheaper minions (that will probably die in combat), so my cards have a maximum effect in every turn. <br>
<br>
